, his behavior became increasingly erratic, and he often sent angry letters to his family from his isolated cabin in rural Montana. During Ted's trial David worked hard to save Ted from the death penalty, and since then he has been a leading activist in the anti-death penalty movement. The book concludes with an afterword by psychiatry professor and forensic psychiatrist James L. Knoll IV, who discusses the current challenges facing the mental health system in the United States as well as the link between mental illness and violence.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aBombers (Terrorists)xFamily relationshipsxUnited States. 0aBombers (Terrorists)xFamily relationshipszUnited States. 0aCapital punishmentxMoral and ethical aspectsxUnited States. 0aCapital punishmentxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Criminals & Outlaws.2bisacsh1 aKnoll, James L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnoll IV, James08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375005zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375005423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375005.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles